eraction. The framework of this volume then continues to explore two more interactions: the Western responses to these practices of shari'a and, in turn, the Muslim legal reaction to these responses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aDomestic relations (Islamic law)zNon-Islamic countries. 0aDomestic relationszWestern countries. 0aMuslimsxLegal status, laws, etc.zNon-Islamic countries. 4aIslam. 4aLaw. 4aSOC. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 7aLAW / Islamic.2bisacsh  aIslamic law, sharia, family law, Islam.1 aAlwani, Zainab, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Maria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerger, Maurits S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoblets, Marie-Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFournier, Pascale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHussain, Jamila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLizzio, Ayat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoors, Annelies, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNielsen, Jørgen S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPossamai, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReyes, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, James T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRohe, Mathias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRutten, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4htt